data.reasoningText:
Now I have a good understanding of the project. Let me plan the component decomposition and implement it.

## Component Plan: Settings Dashboard

### Component Tree
```
Settings                        (page — owns active section, orchestrates layout)
├── SettingsSidebar             (vertical nav tabs)
├── ProfileSection              (profile editing form)
├── NotificationsSection        (notification preferences)
├── SecuritySection             (security settings)
│   ├── ChangePasswordPanel     (expandable password change form)
│   └── RevokeSessionDialog     (confirmation dialog)
└── AppearanceSection           (appearance settings with live preview)


```

### Data Flow
I'm reconsidering the data ownership strategy. Since only one section is visible at a time, it makes more sense for each section to independently load its own data from the service rather than having the page load everything upfront. The page just manages which section is active, and each section handles its own data fetching and updates.

Now I'm planning the implementation order: first the models and service interface with DI registration, then building the section components from the bottom up, followed by the sidebar and main settings page, and finally the CSS isolation files. I'll need a mock service implementation for dependency injection.

Creating all the necessary files now...

```

csharp
// Models and ISettingsService interface
public record UserProfile(string Username, string Email, string FullName);
public record NotificationSettings(bool EmailNotifications, bool PushNotifications);
public record SecuritySettings(string LastPasswordChange, List<string> ActiveSessions);

public interface ISettingsService
{
    Task<UserProfile> GetProfileAsync();
    Task UpdateProfileAsync(UserProfile profile);
    Task<NotificationSettings> GetNotificationsAsync();
    Task UpdateNotificationsAsync(NotificationSettings settings);
    Task<SecuritySettings> GetSecurityAsync();
    Task ChangePasswordAsync(string currentPassword, string newPassword);
    Task RevokeSessionAsync(string sessionId);
}
```

Implementing the mock service and registering in Program.cs...

Building the section components with lazy loading...

Creating the SettingsSidebar with navigation...

Writing the main Settings page orchestrator...

Adding CSS isolation for styling...

